<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[The full document "WHO MERS Global Summary and Assessment of Risk" July 2019 WHO/MERS/RA/19.1 can be found at https://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/handle/10665/326126/WHO-MERS-RA-19.1-eng.pdf?ua=1 and is worth reading.

A key summary point raising awareness and concern in the document: "The continued occurrence of health care-associated outbreaks is deeply concerning and is the result of low awareness and early suspicion of MERS-CoV infections. The non-specificity of MERS symptoms complicates surveillance activities for the virus, often resulting in early missed cases, including the index case, in outbreaks and thereby providing the opportunity for human-to-human transmission in health care settings. Much more emphasis on improving standard IPC practices in all health care facilities is required."

I still wonder WHY Saudi Arabia? Why is Saudi Arabia the epicenter of the MERS-CoV transmission when there are clearly isolated reported events happening in other countries. Most recently, the 2 outbreaks in Oman at the beginning of 2019? And previously there were multiple outbreaks in the UAE. The Korean national returning to South Korea following a business trip to Kuwait and a return via Dubai. Previous cases have been reported with exposure postulated to be in Kuwait, but the history of travel through Dubai may have had exposure while in transit or on the plane(s), as Dubai is one of the central hubs for travel to and from the Middle East. What is different about Saudi Arabia? Is it just a more heightened awareness to suspect MERS-CoV infection so milder cases are identified (much of the time)? Is there a higher background prevalence of co-morbidities such as diabetes that may affect transmission of the virus to and from those with diabetes? Are the animal husbandry practices markedly different, leading to a higher general population indirect exposure? What is the transmissibility of the virus in asymptomatic infections or in mild clinical illness associated with infections? Is this relevant to address the question of why Saudi Arabia? Are there ongoing comparative studies of outbreaks in different countries?

A map showing the countries of the Middle East/Arabian Peninsula can be found at https://www.worldatlas.com/webimage/countrys/asia/arabian.htm. - Mod.MPP]

